@zazugee I 100% agree with you. The point I was trying to make was once you have electricity in a battery the most efficient way to drive a car is an electric motor which is 90-95% efficient. 

Heating up air to drive a Stirling engine in this configuration is at best 10% efficient. If you want a 90% efficiency Stirling engine Carnot says you must have High temperature side at least 10 times higher than exhaust temperature. If you can get exhaust temperature at 300 degrees Kelvin then high side temperature must be >3000 deg Kelvin. 

--- Plainly not easily done! ---

